I see a couple of problems here:

1.- REST Client is always encoding the PATH params. There is an open issue in GH to support the `@Encoded` annotation: https://github.com/quarkusio/quarkus/issues/23961

2.- But, the other problem is that if you use the `@Path` + `@PathParam` annotations, the query params you are using &quot;version=1&amp;modificationDate=1684838964263&amp;cacheVersion=1api=v2&quot; will not be ignored.

You can workaround the above problems by parsing the URI yourself and declaring your client like:

```java
@GET
@Path(&quot;/{part1}/{part2}&quot;)
String call(@PathParam(&quot;part1&quot;) String part1, @PathParam(&quot;part2&quot;) String part2, @RestQuery Map&lt;String, String&gt; queries);
```

However, I think the easiest solution for you is to create a ClientRequestFilter filter that populates the full dynamic URI from a string:

```java
@Provider
public class MyClientRequestFilter implements ClientRequestFilter {

    private static final String HEADER = &quot;dynamic&quot;;

    @Override
    public void filter(ClientRequestContext requestContext) {
        String uri = requestContext.getHeaderString(HEADER);
        if (uri != null) {
            requestContext.setUri(URI.create(requestContext.getUri() + uri));
            requestContext.getHeaders().remove(HEADER);
        }
    }
}
```

Next, declare your client to populate the header that is being used in the filter:

```java
@GET
String call(@HeaderParam(&quot;dynamic&quot;) String dynamic);
```

Btw, you can have more information about the client request filters in https://quarkus.io/version/main/guides/rest-client-reactive#customizing-the-request.

I hope it helps!

 
